response:
Let $\angle BAC = \alpha,$ so $\angle BDC = 3\alpha.$  Since $AB = AC,$ $\angle ABC = \angle ACB = \frac{180^\circ - \alpha}{2}.$  Then
\[\angle ABD = \angle ABC - \angle DBC = \frac{180^\circ - \alpha}{2} - \alpha = 90^\circ - \frac{3\alpha}{2}.\]Also, $\angle BDC = 3\alpha,$ so $\angle BCD = 180^\circ - 3\alpha - \left(90^\circ - \frac{3\alpha}{2}\right) = 90^\circ - \frac{3\alpha}{2}.$  Hence, $\angle ABD = \angle BCD.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
label("$\alpha$", (A + M)/2, W);
label("$3\alpha$", (B + D)/2, SW);
label("$3\alpha$", (D + C)/2, SE);
[/asy]

Since $AB = AC,$ $\angle ABC = \angle ACB,$ so $\angle ACB = \frac{180^\circ - \alpha}{2} = 90^\circ - \frac{\alpha}{2}.$  Then
\[\angle ACD = \angle ACB - \angle DCB = 90^\circ - \frac{\alpha}{2} - \left(90^\circ - \frac{3\alpha}{2}\right) = \alpha.\]Hence, $\triangle ACD$ is isosceles, so $AD = CD = 10.$  Then $BC = 2CD = 20.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, M;

A = (0,11);
D = (0,1);
B = (-11/2,0);
C = (11/2,0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);
draw(B--D--C);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NW);
label("$M$", M, S);
label("$\alpha$", (A + M)/2, W);
label("$3\alpha$", (B + D)/2, SW);
label("$3\alpha$", (D + C)/2, SE);
label("$10$", (A + D)/2, W);
label("$10$", (C + D)/2, E);
[/asy]

Finally, $\angle ABC = 90^\circ - \frac{\alpha}{2} = 90^\circ - \frac{1}{2} \cdot 30^\circ = 75^\circ.$  Then
\[AB = AC = \frac{BC}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{20}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{20\sqrt{3}}{3}.\]The perimeter of $\triangle ABC$ is $AB + AC + BC = \frac{20\sqrt{3}}{3} + \frac{20\sqrt{3}}{3} + 20 = \boxed{\frac{40\sqrt{3} + 60}{3}}.$

